ps://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-486281836.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8728\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-486281836.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-486281836.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-486281836.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-486281836.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 3062px) 100vw, 3062px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eTwo days after the wall was built, 19-year-old Conrad Schumann, an East German border guard, was photographed\u0026nbsp;leaping over barbed wire toward freedom.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"5036\" height=\"3689\" data-id=\"8729\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-548135885.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8729\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-548135885.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-548135885.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-548135885.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-548135885.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 5036px) 100vw, 5036px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eTrain engineer Harry Deterling stole a steam train and drove it through the last station in East Berlin, bringing 25 passengers to the west.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"2782\" height=\"2093\" data-id=\"8730\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542909749.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8730\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542909749.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542909749.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542909749.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542909749.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2782px) 100vw, 2782px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eWolfgang Engels, a 19-year-old East German soldier who had helped build the barbed-wire fences that initially separated both Berlins, stole a tank and drove it through the wall itself.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"3692\" height=\"5376\" data-id=\"8731\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1133470685.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8731\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1133470685.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1133470685.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1133470685.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1133470685.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 3692px) 100vw, 3692px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eDespite getting caught in barbed wire and being shot twice, Engels managed to escape. Here he is pictured being treated at the West Berlin Urban Hospital.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"4852\" height=\"3236\" data-id=\"8732\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-544997637.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8732\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-544997637.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-544997637.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-544997637.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-544997637.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4852px) 100vw, 4852px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eMichael Becker, a GDR refugee is shown with his partner, Holger Bethke (right). They crossed the Berlin Wall in March 1983 by\u0026nbsp;firing an arrow on a fishing line from an attic in East Berlin to a house across the divide.\u0026nbsp;Bethke’s brother, who had already escaped, reeled in the line and connected a steel cable that the pair then zipped across on wooden pulleys.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"5393\" height=\"3968\" data-id=\"8733\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065762108.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8733\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065762108.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065762108.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065762108.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065762108.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 5393px) 100vw, 5393px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eSyrian business man Alfine Fuad (right) shows how he smuggled his soon-to-be-wife Elke Köller (back) and her children Thomas (front) and Heike (middle) through Checkpoint Charlie from East Berlin to the western part of the city on March 16, 1976.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"3357\" height=\"3205\" data-id=\"8734\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542383167.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8734\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542383167.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542383167.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542383167.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542383167.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 3357px) 100vw, 3357px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eA tunnel getaway near the building of the Axel Springer Publishing Company, 1962.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"4582\" height=\"3300\" data-id=\"8735\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-515025068.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8735\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-515025068.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-515025068.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-515025068.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-515025068.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4582px) 100vw, 4582px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eThis picture was issued by East Berlin Communist authorities as they discovered one of the escape tunnels underneath the Wollankastrasse elevated railway station in East Berlin and bordering the French Sector.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"6311\" height=\"4203\" data-id=\"8736\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342120.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8736\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342120.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342120.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342120.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342120.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 6311px) 100vw, 6311px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eOne of the six West Berliners who dug a 20-inch-wide tunnel under a border street to East Berlin crawls out after two hours of digging. Sixteen East Berliners, relatives of the diggers, came through the tunnel dragging an infant behind them in a wash basin. The tunnel was believed to have been discovered a few hours after the 17 reached the West.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"4836\" height=\"6205\" data-id=\"8737\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342126.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8737\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342126.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342126.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342126.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-700342126.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4836px) 100vw, 4836px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eThe tunnel which 28-year-old West Berliner Heinz Jercha and a tiny band of workmen built under the Communist wall was the scene of Jercha\u0026#8217;s death. Jercha was gunned down by East Berlin Communist police as he was helping East Germans escape to West Berlin. Top photo shows how the tunnel of Heldelberger Strasse leads from the basement of a house in the East Berlin sector (right) under the wall to a West Berlin basement in the French sector (left). Bottom photo shows a man kneeling in front of the tunnel entrance in the West Berlin house, eventually sealed by an iron grill.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"3977\" height=\"5394\" data-id=\"8738\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065804744.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8738\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065804744.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065804744.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065804744.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065804744.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 3977px) 100vw, 3977px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003ePictured here is the opening of Tunnel 57, through which 57 people escaped to West Berlin on October 5, 1964.\u0026nbsp;The tunnel was dug from West to East by a group of 20 students led by Joachim Neumann, from a shuttered bakery building on Bernauer Strasse, under the Berlin Wall, to a building 145 meters away on Strelitzer Strasse in East Berlin.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"5100\" height=\"3724\" data-id=\"8739\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630997.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8739\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630997.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630997.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630997.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630997.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 5100px) 100vw, 5100px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eA 75 year-old woman is helped into Tunnel 57.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"4864\" height=\"3907\" data-id=\"8740\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630965.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8740\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630965.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630965.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630965.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730630965.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4864px) 100vw, 4864px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eThe 57 people escaped through this tunnel between October 3-5, 1964. Pictured here is a\u0026nbsp;refugee being winched up to the exit of the tunnel.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"3860\" height=\"5100\" data-id=\"8741\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730631637.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8741\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730631637.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730631637.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730631637.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-730631637.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 3860px) 100vw, 3860px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eRefugees waiting at the basement exit of Tunnel 57, through which 57 East Berlin citizens escaped to the Western sector of the city. The refugees were still very close to the Berlin Wall and could not leave the basement for 24 hours for fear of attracting the attention of East German border guards.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cfigure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"\u003e\u003cimg loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"4054\" height=\"5389\" data-id=\"8742\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065791430.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1\" alt=\"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos\" class=\"wp-image-8742\" srcset=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065791430.jpg?width=300 300w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065791430.jpg?width=1024 1024w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065791430.jpg?width=1536 1536w, https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065791430.jpg?width=2048 2048w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 4054px) 100vw, 4054px\" /\u003e\u003cfigcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"\u003eNot every crossing was successful. The arrow shows the pool of blood at the spot where a man was shot. The 40 to 50-year-old man was shot by East Berlin border guards during his escape attempt at the border corner Bernauer Street/ Berg Street on September 4, 1962.\u003c/figcaption\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\n\u003c/figure\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eThat night, Premier Khrushchev gave the East German government permission to stop the flow of emigrants by closing its border for good. In just two weeks, the East German army, police force and volunteer construction workers had completed a makeshift \u003ca href=\"https://history.phoenix.prod.saymedia.com/news/how-long-was-the-berlin-wall\"\u003ebarbed wire and concrete block wall\u003c/a\u003e–the Berlin Wall–that divided one side of the city from the other.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eBefore the wall was built, Berliners on both sides of the city could move around fairly freely: They crossed the East-West border to work, to shop, to go to the theater and the movies. Trains and subway lines carried passengers back and forth. After the wall was built, it became impossible to get from East to West Berlin except through one of three checkpoints: at Helmstedt (“Checkpoint Alpha” in American military parlance), at Dreilinden (“Checkpoint Bravo”) and in the center of Berlin at Friedrichstrasse (“Checkpoint Charlie”). (Eventually, the GDR built 12 checkpoints along the wall.) At each of the checkpoints, East German soldiers screened diplomats and other officials before they were allowed to enter or leave. Except under special circumstances, travelers from East and West Berlin were rarely allowed across the border.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003ch2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"the-berlin-wall-1961-1989\"\u003eThe Berlin Wall: 1961-1989     \u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe construction of the Berlin Wall did stop the flood of refugees from East to West, and it did defuse the crisis over Berlin. (Though he was not happy about it, President \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/us-presidents/john-f-kennedy\"\u003eJohn F. Kennedy\u003c/a\u003e conceded that “a wall is a hell of a lot better than a war.”) Almost two years after the Berlin Wall was erected, John F. Kennedy delivered one of the most famous addresses of his presidency to a crowd of more than 120,000 gathered outside West Berlin’s city hall, just steps from the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/news/brandenburg-gate-a-brief-history\"\u003eBrandenburg Gate\u003c/a\u003e. Kennedy’s speech has been largely remembered for one particular phrase. \u003ca href=\"http://www.history.com/videos/ask-history-kennedy-and-the-jelly-doughnut\"\u003e“I am a Berliner.”\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eIn all, at least 171 people were killed trying to get over, under or around the Berlin Wall. Escape from East Germany was not impossible, however: From 1961 until the wall came down in 1989, more than 5,000 East Germans (including some 600 border guards) managed to cross the border by jumping out of windows adjacent to the wall, climbing over the barbed wire, flying in hot air balloons, crawling through the sewers and driving through unfortified parts of the wall at high speeds.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003ch2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"the-berlin-wall-the-fall-of-the-wall\"\u003eThe Berlin Wall: The Fall of the Wall     \u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eOn November 9, 1989, as the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/cold-war-history\"\u003eCold War\u003c/a\u003e began to thaw across Eastern Europe, an East German Communist Party spokesman announced a series of new policies regarding border crossings. When pressed on when the changes would take place, he said “As far as I know\u0026#8230; effective immediately, without delay.” East Berliners flocked to border checkpoints, some chanting “Tor auf!” (“Open the gate!”). Within hours, the guards were letting the crowds through, where West Berliners greeted them with flowers and champagne.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eMore than 2 million people from East Berlin visited West Berlin that weekend to participate in a celebration that was, one journalist wrote, “the greatest street party in the history of the world.” People used hammers and picks to knock away chunks of the wall–they became known as “mauerspechte,” or “wall woodpeckers”—while cranes and bulldozers pulled down section after section. Soon the wall was gone and Berlin was united for the first time since 1945. “Only today,” one Berliner spray-painted on a piece of the wall, “is the war really over.”\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe reunification of East and West Germany was made official on October 3, 1990, almost one year after the fall of the Berlin Wall.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\t\t\u003cdiv class=\"block-banner\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003cdiv class=\"block-banner__content\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\u003ch3 class=\"block-banner__heading h4\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\tHISTORY Vault: Declassified: Rise and Fall of the Wall \t\t\t\t\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv class=\"block-banner__text\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003cp\u003eMine formerly guarded vaults and archives around the world to reveal untold stories about the brutal life and catastrophic death of the Berlin Wall, a central symbol of the 20th century\u0026#8217;s longest and deadliest war.\u003c/p\u003e\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cdiv class=\"block-banner__cta\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003ca href=\"https://watch.historyvault.com/specials/declassified-rise-and-fall-of-the-wall/full-special\" class=\"button is-style-alt\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\tWatch now\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/a\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\n\t\t\t\u003cdiv class=\"block-banner__image\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003cimg decoding=\"async\" src=\"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2023/03/Declassified_Rise_and_Fall_Horiz_FIN.jpg?width=1024\u0026#038;height=669\"\u003e\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t\u003c/div\u003e\n\t\t","protected":false,"blocks":[{"clientId":"e456ab06-a0d0-4b80-9c87-336942879518","name":"history/table-of-contents","attributes":{"headings":[{"label":"The Berlin Wall: The Partitioning of Berlin ","anchor":"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/berlin-wall#the-berlin-wall-the-partitioning-of-berlin"},{"label":"The Berlin Wall: Blockade and Crisis ","anchor":"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/berlin-wall#the-berlin-wall-blockade-and-crisis"},{"label":"The Berlin Wall: Building the Wall ","anchor":"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/berlin-wall#the-berlin-wall-building-the-wall"},{"label":"The Berlin Wall: 1961-1989 ","anchor":"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/berlin-wall#the-berlin-wall-1961-1989"},{"label":"The Berlin Wall: The Fall of the Wall ","anchor":"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/berlin-wall#the-berlin-wall-the-fall-of-the-wall"}]},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"a1275130-50ad-4b82-8d4c-0954af084362","name":"history/intro","attributes":[],"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"f9b76c20-4594-4b4a-9c89-d0221424525f","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"On August 13, 1961, the Communist government of the German Democratic Republic (GDR, or East Germany) began to build a barbed wire and concrete “Antifascistischer Schutzwall,” or “antifascist bulwark,” between East and West Berlin. The official purpose of this Berlin Wall was to keep so-called Western “fascists” from entering East Germany and undermining the socialist state, but it primarily served the objective of stemming mass defections from East to West. The Berlin Wall stood until November 9, 1989, when the head of the East German Communist Party announced that citizens of the GDR could cross the border whenever they pleased. That night, ecstatic crowds swarmed the wall. Some crossed freely into West Berlin, while others brought hammers and picks and began to chip away at the wall itself. To this day, the Berlin Wall remains one of the most powerful and enduring symbols of the Cold War.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]}]},{"clientId":"1ba9c7b3-f127-4c99-af40-9f8ef13552a1","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Berlin Wall: The Partitioning of Berlin ","level":2,"id":"the-berlin-wall-the-partitioning-of-berlin"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"40b9e3e2-d948-462f-9f5f-3766e73b6113","name":"history/video","attributes":{"platformId":"1642672707675","duration":0,"contentRating":"","title":"Berlin's Animal Arms Race","disableAutoplay":false,"description":"The Berlin Wall created two separate cities, two sides competing to be the best. And one of their biggest points of pride? Their zoos.","pplId":["235426"],"restrictionId":0,"publicUrl":"https://link.theplatform.com/s/xc6n8B/media/fBRvKvsrvNRH","rating":"TV-PG","poster":"https://cropper.watch.aetnd.com/public-content-aetn.video.aetnd.com/video-thumbnails/AETN-History_VMS/879/791/BRAND_THC_FTBA_235426_SFB_000_2398_5_20191029_01_HD.jpg"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"a6752be9-2d07-45c6-8c9e-41028e4e7296","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"As \u003ca href=\"/topics/world-war-ii\"\u003eWorld War II\u003c/a\u003e came to an end in 1945, a pair of Allied peace conferences at Yalta and Potsdam determined the fate of Germany’s territories. They split the defeated nation into four “allied occupation zones”: The eastern part of the country went to the \u003ca href=\"/topics/history-of-the-soviet-union\"\u003eSoviet Union\u003c/a\u003e, while the western part went to the United States, Great Britain and (eventually) France.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"9df1faee-fe8a-4fbd-9957-20f27b426b79","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Even though Berlin was located entirely within the Soviet part of the country (it sat about 100 miles from the border between the eastern and western occupation zones), the Yalta and Potsdam agreements split the city into similar sectors. The Soviets took the eastern half, while the other Allies took the western. This four-way occupation of Berlin began in June 1945.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"65307e21-4668-4812-9c0c-05f79dc6bbc7","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Berlin Wall: Blockade and Crisis ","level":2,"id":"the-berlin-wall-blockade-and-crisis"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"cc46dd3d-46c0-4eed-8367-e0607ce28405","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The existence of West Berlin, a conspicuously capitalist city deep within communist East Germany, “stuck like a bone in the Soviet throat,” as Soviet leader \u003ca href=\"/topics/cold-war/nikita-sergeyevich-khrushchev\"\u003eNikita Khrushchev\u003c/a\u003e put it. The Russians began maneuvering to drive the United States, Britain and France out of the city for good. In 1948, a Soviet blockade of West Berlin aimed to starve the western Allies out of the city. Instead of retreating, however, the United States and its allies supplied their sectors of the city from the air. This effort, known as the \u003ca href=\"/topics/cold-war/berlin-airlift\"\u003eBerlin Airlift\u003c/a\u003e, lasted for more than a year and delivered more than 2.3 million tons of food, fuel and other goods to West Berlin. The Soviets called off the blockade in 1949.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"3ef0ecb0-b461-467c-b3f6-39bd49852077","name":"core/pullquote","attributes":{"value":"\u003cem\u003eDid you know?\u003c/em\u003e On October 22, 1961, a quarrel between an East German border guard and an American official on his way to the opera in East Berlin very nearly led to what one observer called \"a nuclear-age equivalent of the Wild West Showdown at the O.K. Corral.\" That day, American and Soviet tanks faced off at Checkpoint Charlie for 16 hours. Photographs of the confrontation are some of the most familiar and memorable images of the Cold War.","citation":""},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"ca81f533-f859-4456-a613-4b1c480e8418","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"After a decade of relative calm, tensions flared again in 1958. For the next three years, the Soviets–emboldened by the successful launch of the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/sputnik-launched\"\u003eSputnik\u003c/a\u003e satellite the year before during the “\u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/space-race\"\u003eSpace Race\u003c/a\u003e” and embarrassed by the seemingly endless flow of refugees from east to west (nearly 3 million since the end of the blockade, many of them young skilled workers such as doctors, teachers and engineers)–blustered and made threats, while the Allies resisted. Summits, conferences and other negotiations came and went without resolution. ","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"f7c15f13-f37f-4eb9-9423-cdda3483314a","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Meanwhile, the flood of refugees continued. In June 1961, some 19,000 people left the GDR through Berlin. The following month, 30,000 fled. In the first 11 days of August, 16,000 East Germans crossed the border into West Berlin, and on August 12 some 2,400 followed—the largest number of defectors ever to leave East Germany in a single day.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b933b641-c2a8-4287-acdb-f82717f56dbf","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Berlin Wall: Building the Wall ","level":2,"id":"the-berlin-wall-building-the-wall"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"5fc85522-40ea-4342-abf2-fe35672f6245","name":"core/gallery","attributes":{"columns":2,"linkTo":"none","className":"is-style-slideshow","images":[],"ids":[],"shortCodeTransforms":[],"imageCrop":true,"fixedHeight":true,"sizeSlug":"large","allowResize":false},"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"1991a929-21d9-4c3b-8908-7387792c6348","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":8725,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","credit":"DPA/Picture Alliance/Getty Images","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1060974188.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1","alt":"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos","caption":"East German (or\u0026nbsp;German Democratic Republic) citizens carry only few belongings as they flee to West Berlin. Since the early morning of August 13, 1961, it became known that GDR was separating East Berlin from West Berlin with barbed road blocks and walls.\u0026nbsp;","width":1024,"height":790},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"ee16ec2e-97cb-48f6-afe5-a9aaf2ddab2a","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":8726,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","credit":"Alex Waidmann/ullstein bild/Getty Images","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-542359913.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1","alt":"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos","caption":"Frieda Schulze escapes out of the window of her flat in September 1961. Her apartment building was designated to be in East Berlin, while the street in front of the building was in West Berlin.","width":1024,"height":1392},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"1f243358-0edd-48ac-9d34-3958492efd08","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":8727,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","credit":"Keystone/Getty Images","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-3200289.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1","alt":"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos","caption":"A woman is lowered from a window in Bernauer Strasse on a rope to escape into the western sector of Berlin on September 10, 1961.","width":1024,"height":1450},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"11b6260d-f2bf-4754-8295-98e6ccbde33a","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":8728,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","credit":"Chronos Media GmbH/ullstein bild/Getty Images","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-486281836.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1","alt":"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos","caption":"Two days after the wall was built, 19-year-old Conrad Schumann, an East German border guard, was photographed\u0026nbsp;leaping over barbed wire toward freedom.","width":1024,"height":740},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"552da8ac-c037-4820-ba78-babaf1e508d6","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":8729,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","credit":"Schöne/ullstein bild/Getty Images","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-548135885.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1","alt":"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos","caption":"Train engineer Harry Deterling stole a steam train and 