h 57 East Berlin citizens escaped to the Western sector of the city. The refugees were still very close to the Berlin Wall and could not leave the basement for 24 hours for fear of attracting the attention of East German border guards.\u0026nbsp;","width":1024,"height":1353},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"f3e4ee75-61cd-4959-a598-67ed43caef77","name":"core/image","attributes":{"id":8742,"sizeSlug":"large","linkDestination":"none","credit":"DPA/Picture Alliance/Getty Images","url":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2009/12/berlin-wall-gettyimages-1065791430.jpg?width=800\u0026amp;height=400\u0026amp;crop=2:1","alt":"Crossing the Berlin Wall: Photos","caption":"Not every crossing was successful. The arrow shows the pool of blood at the spot where a man was shot. The 40 to 50-year-old man was shot by East Berlin border guards during his escape attempt at the border corner Bernauer Street/ Berg Street on September 4, 1962.","width":1024,"height":1362},"innerBlocks":[]}]},{"clientId":"8f97d937-f370-4c3d-ae46-a13765d9c64c","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"That night, Premier Khrushchev gave the East German government permission to stop the flow of emigrants by closing its border for good. In just two weeks, the East German army, police force and volunteer construction workers had completed a makeshift \u003ca href=\"https://history.phoenix.prod.saymedia.com/news/how-long-was-the-berlin-wall\"\u003ebarbed wire and concrete block wall\u003c/a\u003e–the Berlin Wall–that divided one side of the city from the other.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"ec732f05-9882-4cee-b2d2-00bee8325db2","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Before the wall was built, Berliners on both sides of the city could move around fairly freely: They crossed the East-West border to work, to shop, to go to the theater and the movies. Trains and subway lines carried passengers back and forth. After the wall was built, it became impossible to get from East to West Berlin except through one of three checkpoints: at Helmstedt (“Checkpoint Alpha” in American military parlance), at Dreilinden (“Checkpoint Bravo”) and in the center of Berlin at Friedrichstrasse (“Checkpoint Charlie”). (Eventually, the GDR built 12 checkpoints along the wall.) At each of the checkpoints, East German soldiers screened diplomats and other officials before they were allowed to enter or leave. Except under special circumstances, travelers from East and West Berlin were rarely allowed across the border.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"e60f65e1-f5e5-41b3-9d9b-ab99ca29328d","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Berlin Wall: 1961-1989 ","level":2,"id":"the-berlin-wall-1961-1989"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"85fc662f-1114-4f4c-b1fc-f3d36cf0b1f8","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The construction of the Berlin Wall did stop the flood of refugees from East to West, and it did defuse the crisis over Berlin. (Though he was not happy about it, President \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/us-presidents/john-f-kennedy\"\u003eJohn F. Kennedy\u003c/a\u003e conceded that “a wall is a hell of a lot better than a war.”) Almost two years after the Berlin Wall was erected, John F. Kennedy delivered one of the most famous addresses of his presidency to a crowd of more than 120,000 gathered outside West Berlin’s city hall, just steps from the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/news/brandenburg-gate-a-brief-history\"\u003eBrandenburg Gate\u003c/a\u003e. Kennedy’s speech has been largely remembered for one particular phrase. \u003ca href=\"http://www.history.com/videos/ask-history-kennedy-and-the-jelly-doughnut\"\u003e“I am a Berliner.”\u003c/a\u003e","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"aec4ba4d-88b9-4433-a542-d56b62fd294e","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In all, at least 171 people were killed trying to get over, under or around the Berlin Wall. Escape from East Germany was not impossible, however: From 1961 until the wall came down in 1989, more than 5,000 East Germans (including some 600 border guards) managed to cross the border by jumping out of windows adjacent to the wall, climbing over the barbed wire, flying in hot air balloons, crawling through the sewers and driving through unfortified parts of the wall at high speeds.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"3ed8b984-c73b-4fff-a805-fc9d63f72844","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"The Berlin Wall: The Fall of the Wall ","level":2,"id":"the-berlin-wall-the-fall-of-the-wall"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"0ffa0c81-d20c-4691-a2cd-5c7c046b223b","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"On November 9, 1989, as the \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/cold-war-history\"\u003eCold War\u003c/a\u003e began to thaw across Eastern Europe, an East German Communist Party spokesman announced a series of new policies regarding border crossings. When pressed on when the changes would take place, he said “As far as I know... effective immediately, without delay.” East Berliners flocked to border checkpoints, some chanting “Tor auf!” (“Open the gate!”). Within hours, the guards were letting the crowds through, where West Berliners greeted them with flowers and champagne.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"753494f9-1ecb-4f64-97bd-56c15d998f62","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"More than 2 million people from East Berlin visited West Berlin that weekend to participate in a celebration that was, one journalist wrote, “the greatest street party in the history of the world.” People used hammers and picks to knock away chunks of the wall–they became known as “mauerspechte,” or “wall woodpeckers”—while cranes and bulldozers pulled down section after section. Soon the wall was gone and Berlin was united for the first time since 1945. “Only today,” one Berliner spray-painted on a piece of the wall, “is the war really over.”","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"fc8ae189-ff70-4125-8f22-9f3ef9a85947","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The reunification of East and West Germany was made official on October 3, 1990, almost one year after the fall of the Berlin Wall.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"e93ff8f3-a7e6-44e5-ae0a-ac0fb9f4165f","name":"corpnews-blocks/banner","attributes":{"heading":"HISTORY Vault: Declassified: Rise and Fall of the Wall ","text":"\u003cp\u003eMine formerly guarded vaults and archives around the world to reveal untold stories about the brutal life and catastrophic death of the Berlin Wall, a central symbol of the 20th century's longest and deadliest war.\u003c/p\u003e","bgMediaID":41870,"bgMediaURL":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2023/03/Declassified_Rise_and_Fall_Horiz_FIN.jpg","ctaEnabled":true,"ctaURL":"https://watch.historyvault.com/specials/declassified-rise-and-fall-of-the-wall/full-special","ctaButtonText":"Watch now","ctaNewTab":false},"innerBlocks":[]}]},"excerpt":{"rendered":"The Berlin Wall was a barbed wire and concrete barrier constructed in 1961 by the Communist government of East Germany at the border of East and West Berlin. The official purpose of the Berlin Wall was to keep Western “fascists” from entering East Germany and undermining the socialist state, but it primarily served the objective of stemming mass defections from East to West.","protected":false},"featured_media":8723,"menu_order":0,"template":"","meta":{"video_platform_id":"","video_duration":0,"video_content_rating":"","video_disable_autoplay":false,"subhead":"","exclude_from_rss":false,"distribute_scheduled_post":[],"curated_related_posts":"","disable_related_posts":""},"tags":[],"article_type":[],"story_byline":[406],"attribute":[8],"story_category":[64],"article_type_meta":"","tags_meta":"","disable_interrupter":"","primary_term":null,"video_thumbnail":false,"hide_on_google_news":false,"yoast_head_json":{"title":"Berlin Wall | HISTOR